# StarVault Whitepaper Draft
StarVault Protocol Whitepaper v0.1
Title

StarVault Protocol (SVP)

Building the Data Sovereignty Layer for the AI Age
Executive Summary

The internet has become the largest data generation engine in human history. Yet individuals have little ownership, visibility, or control over the personal information they create.

As artificial intelligence systems increasingly depend on personal data, the need for a new framework for ownership and consent becomes critical.

StarVault Protocol (SVP) is an open protocol that enables user-owned, permission-based access to personal data through cryptographic identity, consent management, and auditable access controls.

SVP aims to establish ownership and consent as native features of the internet.

1. Introduction

The modern internet solved communication.

It did not solve ownership.

Today:

Users generate data
Platforms collect data
Platforms monetize data
Users have limited control

This model has enabled rapid innovation but has also concentrated power over personal information.

StarVault proposes a new model:

Data should be owned by individuals and accessed through explicit, revocable permission.

2. Problem Statement

Current digital systems suffer from five structural problems:

Centralized Ownership

Personal data is controlled by platforms rather than users.

Permanent Access

Permissions are often difficult to revoke.

Lack of Transparency

Users rarely know how their data is being used.

Data Duplication

The same data is copied across hundreds of systems.

AI-Era Risk

AI increases the value and sensitivity of personal data.

3. Vision

We envision a future where:

Individuals own digital assets
Applications request access
Consent is machine-readable
Access is temporary
Usage is auditable
Ownership remains with the creator
4. Core Principles
Ownership

Users retain ownership of their data.

Consent

Access requires explicit authorization.

Transparency

All access events are visible.

Revocability

Permissions can be withdrawn.

Interoperability

Applications can integrate through open standards.

